00:07:34.190 --> 00:07:38.640
Born in Ghana in 1962, Kwame
Dawes spent most of his childhood

00:07:38.640 --> 00:07:41.330
and early adult life in Jamaica.

00:07:41.330 --> 00:07:45.020
He is the author of over 30
books, and his 16 collections

00:07:45.020 --> 00:07:49.210
of poetry include "Progeny of Air,"
winner of the Ford Poetry Prize

00:07:49.210 --> 00:07:52.890
for best first collection in
the U.K., and "Duppy Conqueror,

00:07:52.890 --> 00:07:55.490
New and Selected Poems,"
published just a few years ago

00:07:55.490 --> 00:07:57.620
by Copper Canyon Press.

00:07:57.620 --> 00:08:00.090
Dawes' novels include
"She's Gone" and "Bivouac."

00:08:00.090 --> 00:08:03.490
And his non-fiction
collections include "A Far Cry

00:08:03.490 --> 00:08:06.260
from Plymouth Rock, a
Personal Narrative,"

00:08:06.260 --> 00:08:08.920
and "Fugue and Other Writings."

00:08:08.920 --> 00:08:13.840
The editor of several anthologies,
Dawes is also an actor, playwright,

00:08:13.840 --> 00:08:17.690
and producer, an accomplished
storyteller and broadcaster,

00:08:17.690 --> 00:08:21.740
and the lead singer in
Ujamaa, a reggae band.

00:08:21.740 --> 00:08:25.100
Fifteen of his plays have
been produced, and in 2009,

00:08:25.100 --> 00:08:29.420
Dawes won an Emmy for
livehopelove.com,

00:08:29.420 --> 00:08:34.230
an interactive site based on his
Pulitzer Center project, "Hope,

00:08:34.230 --> 00:08:36.990
Living and Loving with
AIDS in Jamaica."

00:08:36.990 --> 00:08:42.410
Dawes' other honors include the
Hurston/Wright Legacy Award,

00:08:42.410 --> 00:08:46.440
the Poets and Writers Barnes and
Noble Writers for Writers Award,

00:08:46.440 --> 00:08:49.260
and a Guggenheim Foundation
Fellowship.

00:08:49.260 --> 00:08:52.390
In 2004, he received the
Musgrave Silver Medal

00:08:52.390 --> 00:08:54.690
for contribution to
the arts in Jamaica.

00:08:54.690 --> 00:08:59.220
And in 2008, the Elizabeth O'Neill
Verner Governor's Award for service

00:08:59.220 --> 00:09:01.430
to the arts in South Carolina.

00:09:01.430 --> 00:09:06.280
In 2009, he was inducted into the
South Carolina Academy of Authors.

00:09:06.280 --> 00:09:10.680
Kwame Dawes is currently the Glenna
Luschei Editor of Prairie Schooner

00:09:10.680 --> 00:09:12.780
and Chancellor's Professor
of English

00:09:12.780 --> 00:09:15.250
at the University of Nebraska.

00:09:15.250 --> 00:09:17.050
The co-founder and
programming director

00:09:17.050 --> 00:09:20.960
of the Calabash International
Literary Festival, he also teaches

00:09:20.960 --> 00:09:25.260 position:56%
in the Pacific MFA Writing Program,
and is on the faculty of Cave Canem.

00:09:25.260 --> 00:09:29.110
He is also the founder of
the African Poetry Book Fund,

00:09:29.110 --> 00:09:31.970
which promotes and advances
the development and publication

00:09:31.970 --> 00:09:36.800
of the poetic arts through its
book series, contests, workshops,

00:09:36.800 --> 00:09:40.350
and seminars, and through its
collaboration with publishers,

00:09:40.350 --> 00:09:43.990 position:56%
festivals, booking agents,
colleges, universities, conferences,

00:09:43.990 --> 00:09:46.850
and all other entities
that share an interest

00:09:46.850 --> 00:09:48.360
in the poetic arts of Africa.

00:09:48.360 --> 00:09:51.550
