00:10:13.460 --> 00:10:15.270
&gt;&gt; Kwame Dawes: So good afternoon.

00:10:15.270 --> 00:10:16.570
&gt;&gt; Good afternoon.

00:10:16.570 --> 00:10:17.870
&gt;&gt; Kwame Dawes: It's
good to be here.

00:10:17.870 --> 00:10:25.620 position:56%
It's a beautiful space, and I thank
Rob for initiating this conversation

00:10:25.620 --> 00:10:29.940
that I hope will continue through a
series of collaborations and so on.

00:10:29.940 --> 00:10:32.730
We had a great dinner last night.

00:10:32.730 --> 00:10:39.580 position:56%
And it is always good to find people
who value language and poetry.

00:10:39.580 --> 00:10:48.760
And as I've always said, poetry
is not the answer to everything.

00:10:48.760 --> 00:10:53.180
I think people who see poetry as
their religion are unfortunate.

00:10:53.180 --> 00:10:59.040
But there is a time
when a poem is needed.

00:10:59.040 --> 00:11:02.350
And when it's needed, it's
the only thing that's needed,

00:11:02.350 --> 00:11:04.560
and it's the only thing
that will work.

00:11:04.560 --> 00:11:07.910
And I believe this sincerely,
and I believe this completely.

00:11:07.910 --> 00:11:11.790
I also believe that
our art is a product

00:11:11.790 --> 00:11:16.390
that generates this
remarkable thing called empathy.

00:11:16.390 --> 00:11:19.740
Not only generates it, but
it trains us in empathy.

00:11:19.740 --> 00:11:24.490
The truth is that all
acts of hatred, of racism,

00:11:24.490 --> 00:11:28.800
of bigotry are predicated
fundamentally on a lack

00:11:28.800 --> 00:11:31.290
of imagination and incapacity

00:11:31.290 --> 00:11:34.170
to imagine what somebody
else is feeling.

00:11:34.170 --> 00:11:36.360
That's the function of empathy.

00:11:36.360 --> 00:11:43.530 position:56%
It is possible to have that capacity
eroded, and in fact, destroyed,

00:11:43.530 --> 00:11:48.000
and ultimately stopped in people
if they do not have the chance

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:51.160
to exercise this capacity
for empathy.

00:11:51.160 --> 00:11:55.140
And I think in the wisdom
of our millions of ancestors

00:11:55.140 --> 00:11:59.070
over thousands, and thousands,
and millions of years,

00:11:59.070 --> 00:12:02.770
we understood in our bodies that
the way to do so is through art,

00:12:02.770 --> 00:12:05.550
through music, and
through the imagination.

00:12:05.550 --> 00:12:09.170
The more we kindle the imagination,
the greater our capacity

00:12:09.170 --> 00:12:10.950
to hurt and damage each other.

00:12:10.950 --> 00:12:13.610
So this is my way of
saying it's good

00:12:13.610 --> 00:12:16.240
that they pay me to write poems.

00:12:17.430 --> 00:12:19.460
I'm saving the world.

00:12:19.460 --> 00:12:26.030
I'll just read a few poems, and I
look forward to the conversation

00:12:26.030 --> 00:12:27.440
that we'll have in a minute.

00:12:27.440 --> 00:12:32.450
You know, my story is -- I
like to think it's interesting

00:12:32.450 --> 00:12:37.280
because it's a challenging story.

00:12:37.280 --> 00:12:40.250
I was born in Ghana in West Africa.

00:12:40.250 --> 00:12:42.860
I grew up there until I
was about 10 years old,

00:12:42.860 --> 00:12:44.960
and then eventually
we moved to Jamaica.

00:12:44.960 --> 00:12:49.260
So then I grew up also in Jamaica,
and then eventually left Jamaica

00:12:49.260 --> 00:12:51.870
as a grown man to study in Canada.

00:12:51.870 --> 00:12:56.920
And then I've lived in
the U.S. since 1992.

00:12:56.920 --> 00:12:59.880
There's a way in which my
journey and the narrative

00:12:59.880 --> 00:13:06.230 position:56%
of my journey is an echo of journeys
that those before me had made.

00:13:06.230 --> 00:13:10.070
And here I talk about the
Middle Passage, that journey,

00:13:10.070 --> 00:13:16.250
that forced journey that brought
Africans to the New World.

00:13:16.250 --> 00:13:20.970
But even later than that, my own
grandfather, in about the turn

00:13:20.970 --> 00:13:26.840
of the century, about 1905,
1906, decided to work --

00:13:26.840 --> 00:13:32.960
to take on a gig with the
Colonial Office to go to Nigeria

00:13:32.960 --> 00:13:34.720
to work there in Nigeria.

00:13:34.720 --> 00:13:41.230
And he went -- he worked in
Southern Nigeria in Warri.

00:13:41.230 --> 00:13:48.190
And there he littered the place
with a bunch of children, and --

00:13:48.190 --> 00:13:51.920
including my father who was
born actually in Nigeria.

00:13:51.920 --> 00:13:55.780
So it turns out I'm
actually Nigerian,

00:13:55.780 --> 00:14:01.700
which is not something I say a
lot, but when it's necessary,

00:14:01.700 --> 00:14:04.290
because you know, Nigerians
are very powerful people.

00:14:04.290 --> 00:14:07.300
So when it's convenient
I make the association.

00:14:07.300 --> 00:14:10.780 position:56%
They're also annoying, so that's the
other reason why I struggle with it.

00:14:10.780 --> 00:14:14.100
But one can say the same thing
about -- decidedly about Jamaicans.

00:14:14.100 --> 00:14:15.400
Not Ghanaians.

00:14:15.400 --> 00:14:18.430
Ghanaians are always sweet.

00:14:18.430 --> 00:14:23.510
So anyway, that journey was
interesting because in a sense,

00:14:23.510 --> 00:14:27.450
he lived in Nigeria for about --
he and his family lived in Nigeria

00:14:27.450 --> 00:14:30.360 position:56%
for about 15 years, almost 20 years.

00:14:30.360 --> 00:14:32.060
And then my father
did the same thing.

00:14:32.060 --> 00:14:34.920
Having been born in
Nigeria, he lived in Jamaica,

00:14:34.920 --> 00:14:38.390
grew up in Jamaica, because
when he got to Jamaica

00:14:38.390 --> 00:14:42.020
in 1928 he was just
about two years old.

00:14:42.020 --> 00:14:45.590
But then he went back to Ghana,
and that's how I came about,

00:14:45.590 --> 00:14:48.580
because he married my
mother who is Ghanaian.

00:14:48.580 --> 00:14:49.880
And they had children.

00:14:49.880 --> 00:14:52.420
And he also lived in
Ghana for 15 years.

00:14:52.420 --> 00:14:55.850
This idea of migrations across --

00:14:55.850 --> 00:14:58.710
that conversations
throughout this African --

00:14:58.710 --> 00:15:03.100
Africa and its diaspora is
built into my body and my life.

00:15:03.100 --> 00:15:07.820
And so my whole work is about
speaking from a perspective

00:15:07.820 --> 00:15:10.720
that recognizes an
entity called Africanness,

00:15:10.720 --> 00:15:15.070
an entity that is Pan-African,
that is global,

00:15:15.070 --> 00:15:17.520
that recognizes the
traces, and the dignity,

00:15:17.520 --> 00:15:19.580
and the history of African people.

00:15:19.580 --> 00:15:22.570
And yet, it is comfortable
in the idea of movement,

00:15:22.570 --> 00:15:24.780
and in the idea of migration.

00:15:24.780 --> 00:15:27.070
And so my work is about
making those connections.

00:15:27.070 --> 00:15:28.610
It's not a crisis for me.

00:15:28.610 --> 00:15:31.050
It's not a conflict for me.

00:15:31.050 --> 00:15:33.670
It is not a struggle
to understand myself.

00:15:33.670 --> 00:15:34.970
I get myself.

00:15:34.970 --> 00:15:36.370
I understand who I am.

00:15:36.370 --> 00:15:39.760
I know, as Bob Marley says,
where I'm coming from.

00:15:39.760 --> 00:15:44.470 position:56%
So you know, I wouldn't have to ask
you, "Who the hell do I think I am?"

00:15:44.470 --> 00:15:47.000
I know who I am.

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:48.300
I'm a buffalo.

00:15:48.300 --> 00:15:52.490
I'm going to start singing.

00:15:52.490 --> 00:15:57.180
So my poetry reflects that, and
I'll read a few poems that do that.

00:15:57.180 --> 00:16:00.260
But I wanted to start with
a poem for Kofi Awoonor.

00:16:00.260 --> 00:16:07.150
Kofi Awoonor was a cousin,
related to my mother,

00:16:07.150 --> 00:16:08.960
a dear friend of my father.

00:16:08.960 --> 00:16:16.890 position:56%
And when Kofi was killed in Kenya
several years ago during that attack

00:16:16.890 --> 00:16:22.360 position:56%
at the mall in Nairobi, I was there.

00:16:22.360 --> 00:16:25.770
We were waiting for him to
come and do a reading, in fact,

00:16:25.770 --> 00:16:29.980
because I had arranged for
him to come to Storymoja,

00:16:29.980 --> 00:16:32.520
because we had just
published his book of poems,

00:16:32.520 --> 00:16:35.210
his "New and Selected Poems."

00:16:35.210 --> 00:16:39.170
So then we got the news
that he could not be found.

00:16:39.170 --> 00:16:44.230 position:56%
And later on that night we found out
that he had died and been killed.

00:16:44.230 --> 00:16:46.850
It's a painful recollection,
a painful memory,

00:16:46.850 --> 00:16:52.170
because part of it was the sort of
struggle of knowing that I was --

00:16:52.170 --> 00:16:56.020
you know, I had asked
him to come to Nairobi.

00:16:56.020 --> 00:16:59.120
But I took great comfort, you know,

00:16:59.120 --> 00:17:00.600
because I know the
family quite well,

00:17:00.600 --> 00:17:02.180
in the fact that he
wanted to be there.

00:17:02.180 --> 00:17:05.060
And it was a chance
for me to see him again

00:17:05.060 --> 00:17:07.050
and to actually show him
the cover of the book,

00:17:07.050 --> 00:17:08.960
because the book hadn't
been printed --

00:17:08.960 --> 00:17:10.840
that we showed him
the cover of the book.

00:17:10.840 --> 00:17:14.970
And he was elated and
just felt good about it.

00:17:14.970 --> 00:17:17.980
But I -- so I like
to being my readings

00:17:17.980 --> 00:17:19.540
with a poem dedicated to him.

00:17:19.540 --> 00:17:21.070
This is a little small poem --

00:17:21.070 --> 00:17:22.850
not a poem dedicated,
a poem that he wrote.

00:17:22.850 --> 00:17:25.640
This is a small poem
called "Counting the Years,"

00:17:25.640 --> 00:17:28.820
and it's by Kofi Awoonor.

00:17:28.820 --> 00:17:33.260 position:56%
"As usual, as in the earlier dreams,
I come to the whistling shores,

00:17:33.260 --> 00:17:36.710
the voice of the high-domed
crab stilled.

00:17:36.710 --> 00:17:41.890
But a chorus remains of the
water creatures of earlier times,

00:17:41.890 --> 00:17:44.970
of the birth time and
the dying time,

00:17:44.970 --> 00:17:47.990
the pity when we resurrect
the travelers,

00:17:47.990 --> 00:17:52.220
the anchorman on our singular
boat that will take us home."

00:18:01.260 --> 00:18:03.770
Here's a poem called
"After Acceptance."

00:18:03.770 --> 00:18:06.590
It's a poem for my father.

00:18:06.590 --> 00:18:09.430
"Then I read the monumental
legend of her love

00:18:09.430 --> 00:18:11.700
and grasp her wrinkled hands."

00:18:11.700 --> 00:18:15.620
It's a quote from one of his poems.

00:18:15.620 --> 00:18:20.460 position:56%
"You were a child there from two to
introverted 10, crafting your dreams

00:18:20.460 --> 00:18:23.990
from tattered books teacher
Dawes crammed into his shelves.

00:18:23.990 --> 00:18:26.660
Your brother was a knight,
and your sisters princesses,

00:18:26.660 --> 00:18:30.450
and you write verse because
you longed for friends.

00:18:30.450 --> 00:18:33.770
Curled in the cool underpart of
the creaking house on the hill,

00:18:33.770 --> 00:18:38.370
you battled chickens for space to
sketch the worlds in your head.

00:18:38.370 --> 00:18:39.790
We drove there together once.

00:18:39.790 --> 00:18:43.920
You, proud of the recollections
stirred, endeared each sharp bend

00:18:43.920 --> 00:18:46.160
in the road with names
like Breadfruit Curve,

00:18:46.160 --> 00:18:50.110
Star Apple Corner,
and Tamarind Arch.

00:18:50.110 --> 00:18:52.450
Your laughter was nervous
nearing the house,

00:18:52.450 --> 00:18:57.190
the child in you drumming a rhythm
on the sweat-slick steering wheel.

00:18:57.190 --> 00:19:00.140
On the slack porch, you pointed
through breadfruit leaves

00:19:00.140 --> 00:19:01.980 position:56%
to the faded line of the sea and sky

00:19:01.980 --> 00:19:05.940
where Cuba wavered
in the midday haze.

00:19:05.940 --> 00:19:08.280
From there as a child
you learned of otherness,

00:19:08.280 --> 00:19:11.830
worlds beyond the house
afloat in a sea of green.

00:19:11.830 --> 00:19:15.340
From there your home became
a point from which to leap.

00:19:15.340 --> 00:19:20.320
I walk the overgrown paths where,
fired with Arthurian legends,

00:19:20.320 --> 00:19:23.600
you galloped, mad-child on
a wild, irreverent steed,

00:19:23.600 --> 00:19:27.290
dizzy in the patchwork of
sunlight through the branches.

00:19:27.290 --> 00:19:30.890
The thought of you as child
is real as the trees towering.

00:19:30.890 --> 00:19:34.200
And staring upward, I trace
your steps, avoiding the trunks

00:19:34.200 --> 00:19:38.130 position:56%
by the pattern of leaves in the sky.

00:19:38.130 --> 00:19:41.060
The child overwhelms
my straight-back logic,

00:19:41.060 --> 00:19:45.240
and suddenly I am sprinting,
beating hoofbeats against my chest,

00:19:45.240 --> 00:19:50.650
light blazing green on my face, my
shouts echoed in the tree trunks.

00:19:50.650 --> 00:19:55.800
On the barbecue, dry
brown pimento beans roast.

00:19:55.800 --> 00:19:57.960
The ancient chair she
sat in is there

00:19:57.960 --> 00:20:02.560
where a rotting orange tree
leans and sheds brittle leaves.

00:20:02.560 --> 00:20:07.200
The chair is light and fading,
sucked dry by sun and salt wind.

00:20:07.200 --> 00:20:09.850
I can see her, bandannaed there,

00:20:09.850 --> 00:20:13.250
sharp calico against
the hill's gray,

00:20:13.250 --> 00:20:17.970
her wrinkled hands outstretched,
trembling, her eyes glowing.

00:20:17.970 --> 00:20:22.310
Maybe your ghosts hover
above the house a night,

00:20:22.310 --> 00:20:25.110
but I came at daytime,
so I'm not sure.

00:20:25.110 --> 00:20:29.730
But teachers, you taught me much
in the lesson of your silent ways.

00:20:29.730 --> 00:20:35.500
While there, I smelled ink, and
the dust sneezed is chalk dust.

00:20:35.500 --> 00:20:39.340
Your world was a noble one,
you cloud of holy witnesses

00:20:39.340 --> 00:20:44.420
who sought new worlds to
replace the chain-link silences.

00:20:44.420 --> 00:20:48.830
Daily Bible verses etched on
your brow, missionary zeal,

00:20:48.830 --> 00:20:51.780
and gave strength to
your upright eyes.

00:20:51.780 --> 00:20:54.650
Now you hover above
this house that crumbles

00:20:54.650 --> 00:20:57.320
where the wood ticks termites.

00:20:57.320 --> 00:21:00.840
Maybe, grand ones, your
ghosts linger above the house,

00:21:00.840 --> 00:21:02.800
meeting there, then
together swoop down,

00:21:02.800 --> 00:21:07.100
one wind lifting a tattered
sheet's edge, one animation,

00:21:07.100 --> 00:21:12.200
now a brilliant O, cooling
with a breath the sheen of toil

00:21:12.200 --> 00:21:16.020
on some weary back, shifting
breadfruit leaves to a rustling

00:21:16.020 --> 00:21:20.110
as eyes turn upward, smiling
at the cool, not at you,

00:21:20.110 --> 00:21:22.870
not knowing that ghosts are wind.

00:21:22.870 --> 00:21:25.040
You return morose,
having done your part

00:21:25.040 --> 00:21:29.220
of touching the living before dawn
and getting little thanks for it.

00:21:29.220 --> 00:21:32.570
You return to your tombs in which
you were sheltered from the swelter

00:21:32.570 --> 00:21:39.100
of sun and the tramping of my
feet now in the gray and green.

00:21:39.100 --> 00:21:45.230
I praise the dream of Sturge Town
and the silent homecoming it was.

00:21:45.230 --> 00:21:50.210
I praise the songs of the ghosts
sealed in my mind's chrysalis.

00:21:50.210 --> 00:21:54.280
I praise the constant leaves
spinning in the pure air.

00:21:54.280 --> 00:22:00.170 position:56%
I praise the hands that birthed you,
worn as they were, for they glowed,

00:22:00.170 --> 00:22:05.160
stained red with first blood
spilled into this navel-string

00:22:05.160 --> 00:22:08.830
where for years the ancient
red-barked trees have stood.

00:22:08.830 --> 00:22:13.630
I praise these things freed
by your wrinkled hands."

00:22:13.630 --> 00:22:18.880
I'll read two more poems.

00:22:18.880 --> 00:22:21.190
That should do the trick.

00:22:21.190 --> 00:22:23.850
This is a poem called
"African Postman."

00:22:23.850 --> 00:22:31.020
Some years ago I was invited
by the BBC to write a piece

00:22:31.020 --> 00:22:34.600
about Haile Selassie
to do a documentary.

00:22:34.600 --> 00:22:37.930
It's actually for radio,
for BBC Four.

00:22:37.930 --> 00:22:41.650
And the idea was that I would do
a documentary about his period

00:22:41.650 --> 00:22:44.480
in exile in Bath, England.

00:22:44.480 --> 00:22:47.510
So I was going to go
to Bath and, I guess,

00:22:47.510 --> 00:22:50.150
talk to some people
at Bath, and so on.

00:22:50.150 --> 00:22:53.550
And then I thought, "Well,
I should go to Ethiopia.

00:22:53.550 --> 00:22:55.920
I mean, what's -- how do
you -- what's the point?

00:22:55.920 --> 00:22:58.070
And you know, BBC is paying."

00:22:58.070 --> 00:23:02.600
So I convinced them to pay
for me to go to Ethiopia.

00:23:02.600 --> 00:23:05.560
And I did, and it was one of the
most beautiful and powerful times.

00:23:05.560 --> 00:23:09.980
I got to talk to all kinds
of people who knew him.

00:23:09.980 --> 00:23:12.860
And this is a poem
called "African Postman."

00:23:12.860 --> 00:23:15.630
It's dedicated to a man
called Solomon Ephraim Woolfe.

00:23:15.630 --> 00:23:16.930
I met him.

00:23:16.930 --> 00:23:19.220
He was a Jamaican living
in Sheshemane.

00:23:19.220 --> 00:23:23.310
That, you know, 500 acres of
land that Selassie had ceded

00:23:23.310 --> 00:23:27.750 position:56%
over to anybody from the diaspora
who wanted to go back to Ethiopia --

00:23:27.750 --> 00:23:30.470
or go back to Africa to live.

00:23:30.470 --> 00:23:34.300
And Solomon Woolfe was a Jamaican
who was one of those Rastas

00:23:34.300 --> 00:23:37.040
that decided to take him up on it.

00:23:37.040 --> 00:23:38.710
And I asked him some questions,

00:23:38.710 --> 00:23:41.500
and then came the most
troubling question, which was --

00:23:41.500 --> 00:23:47.170
my question to him was how did
it feel when Haile Selassie died,

00:23:47.170 --> 00:23:50.850
which is not a question
you ask a Rastafarian.

00:23:50.850 --> 00:23:53.650
So "Africa Postman."

00:23:53.650 --> 00:23:55.250
"Son, who is that?

00:23:55.250 --> 00:23:57.640
Is the African Postman, Daddy.

00:23:57.640 --> 00:24:00.290
Burning Spear.

00:24:00.290 --> 00:24:03.410
East from Addis Ababa then
south deep into the Rift Valley,

00:24:03.410 --> 00:24:08.020
I can hear the horns trumpeting
over the flat-roofed acacia trees,

00:24:08.020 --> 00:24:11.140
see the African women bend low
with wood heavy on their backs,

00:24:11.140 --> 00:24:14.730
and the cows, goats, donkeys,
mules sheep, and horses snapped

00:24:14.730 --> 00:24:19.860
into obedient herds by sprinting
children moving along the roadside.

00:24:19.860 --> 00:24:21.330
Life happens here.

00:24:21.330 --> 00:24:24.300
I am travelling to the land I
have heard about, Sheshemane,

00:24:24.300 --> 00:24:27.700
the green place, 500 acres
of Jah's benevolence.

00:24:27.700 --> 00:24:31.510
And I know now that I long to
hear the rootsman tell me how,

00:24:31.510 --> 00:24:34.740
despite rumors of his passing,
the natty keeps on riding,

00:24:34.740 --> 00:24:37.230
keeps on standing in the
fields of praise to hold

00:24:37.230 --> 00:24:39.920
onto the faith of roots people.

00:24:39.920 --> 00:24:42.600
Brother Solomon, you put the
name Ephraim on your head

00:24:42.600 --> 00:24:44.500
and carry the face
of the true Rasta,

00:24:44.500 --> 00:24:48.100
the face of an Ashanti warrior,
eyes deep under heavy lids,

00:24:48.100 --> 00:24:50.380
and your skin tight as
leather, blacker than black.

00:24:50.380 --> 00:24:54.540 position:56%
I have met you before on the streets
of Kingston, there where you trod

00:24:54.540 --> 00:24:56.710
to the hiss and slander
of the heathen.

00:24:56.710 --> 00:24:59.830
You, natty dread, gathering
the people's broken minds

00:24:59.830 --> 00:25:01.250
into your calabash.

00:25:01.250 --> 00:25:04.410
You carry it all, tell
them, "Return to the roots,

00:25:04.410 --> 00:25:06.600
the healing shall take place."

00:25:06.600 --> 00:25:10.240
You are Burning Spear's
voice in the fields of teff.

00:25:10.240 --> 00:25:13.280
You tell me of the prophecy of
Marcus, and I listen to you,

00:25:13.280 --> 00:25:15.230
through the phlegm, through
the gruff of your voice.

00:25:15.230 --> 00:25:18.420
And suddenly when I ask you
about the passing of the Emperor,

00:25:18.420 --> 00:25:22.900 position:56%
you rise up like a staff of
correction, your voice reaching back

00:25:22.900 --> 00:25:26.740
to the mountains, your warrior
self, our yardman greatness,

00:25:26.740 --> 00:25:31.120
and you speak a mystery of those
who have ears but won't hear,

00:25:31.120 --> 00:25:33.020
and those who have
eyes and won't see.

00:25:33.020 --> 00:25:36.940
And I know that this dread
will one day stand in this soil

00:25:36.940 --> 00:25:42.000
and find his feet growing roots,
that soon the earth will be darker

00:25:42.000 --> 00:25:43.860
for the arrival of Solomon.

00:25:43.860 --> 00:25:47.440
Oh, let the heathen rage,
let the doubters scoff,

00:25:47.440 --> 00:25:51.860
let this Ghanaian youth whose eyes
have seen the face of Jesus Christ,

00:25:51.860 --> 00:25:54.790
let him, too, sit and marvel
at the faith of the natty.

00:25:54.790 --> 00:25:58.970
For this African postman has
forsaken father and mother,

00:25:58.970 --> 00:26:02.660
and has come to stand
before His Imperial Majesty,

00:26:02.660 --> 00:26:06.270
to call only him father, so that
the father might call him son,

00:26:06.270 --> 00:26:09.470
and the world will carry
on its weary march.

00:26:09.470 --> 00:26:12.700
And the ibises will swoop
in the Ethiopian dusk,

00:26:12.700 --> 00:26:16.410
and the smoke will rise from the
wood fires, and the night will come

00:26:16.410 --> 00:26:20.770
with the news that the
rootsman, after 400 years

00:26:20.770 --> 00:26:24.040
of being told he's
homeless, has come home.

00:26:24.040 --> 00:26:26.190
Yes, Jah, has come home.

00:26:26.190 --> 00:26:30.230
Sons and daughters of His
Imperial Majesty Haile Selassie,

00:26:30.230 --> 00:26:35.340
Earth Rightful Ruler, without
any apology say, this is the time

00:26:35.340 --> 00:26:38.760
when I, and I, and I, and
I should come home, yes,

00:26:38.760 --> 00:26:42.700
Jah, oh, come a holy foe.

00:26:42.700 --> 00:26:49.050
Nah leggo, nah leggo, nah leggo."

00:26:49.050 --> 00:26:56.490
Okay, so I'll end with
a poem called "Rope."

00:26:56.490 --> 00:26:58.020
I was happy to see when I went

00:26:58.020 --> 00:27:02.090
to the African American
Museum yesterday that --

00:27:02.090 --> 00:27:06.690
you know, I was nervous
going in because I said --

00:27:06.690 --> 00:27:08.420
I went to the theater
section, and I said,

00:27:08.420 --> 00:27:12.070
"I they don't feature
[inaudible] and August Wilson,

00:27:12.070 --> 00:27:14.500
I'm burning the place down."

00:27:14.500 --> 00:27:18.280
And I was happy to see
that they recognized.

00:27:18.280 --> 00:27:19.580
So those two are featured.

00:27:19.580 --> 00:27:23.390
August Wilson is the center of a
new collection of poems that comes

00:27:23.390 --> 00:27:26.600
out this year from the
[inaudible] from me called,

00:27:26.600 --> 00:27:28.970
"City of Bones, a Testament."

00:27:28.970 --> 00:27:33.020
And this poem called "Rope" is a
response to August Wilson's work.

00:27:33.020 --> 00:27:35.690
Some of the work I've done, the
academic work, the scholarly work,

00:27:35.690 --> 00:27:40.950
is to talk about August Wilson's
engagements in African aesthetics,

00:27:40.950 --> 00:27:42.630
the idea of diaspora,
the aesthetics,

00:27:42.630 --> 00:27:45.610
but particularly the African
aesthetics in his work.

00:27:45.610 --> 00:27:50.150
But his poems -- his plays are
remarkable, just an amazing thing.

00:27:50.150 --> 00:27:51.820
So this poem is called "Rope."

00:27:51.820 --> 00:27:54.880
I usually read the last few
lines of the poem first,

00:27:54.880 --> 00:27:57.750
and then I'll come
back and start again.

00:27:57.750 --> 00:27:59.840
So this is how the poem ends.

00:27:59.840 --> 00:28:03.090
"Someday a soul will
come out of the fields

00:28:03.090 --> 00:28:07.570
to claim it, and then we will know.

00:28:07.570 --> 00:28:10.290
Someday a soul will
come out of the fields

00:28:10.290 --> 00:28:14.270
to claim it, and then we will know.

00:28:14.270 --> 00:28:18.000
To hold our lives together on
the cart before the slow march

00:28:18.000 --> 00:28:21.140
after midnight along
backroads, blind-driving,

00:28:21.140 --> 00:28:24.570
the scent of the exhaust
making us drowsy,

00:28:24.570 --> 00:28:28.780
every shadow in the fields a
threat of sorts, we use rope thick

00:28:28.780 --> 00:28:32.860
as two thumbs side by side, pulling
hard on the knot to keep our parts

00:28:32.860 --> 00:28:35.590
from falling by the wayside.

00:28:35.590 --> 00:28:38.510
We have kept this rope supple
with oil, constant use,

00:28:38.510 --> 00:28:42.020
never letting it stay
idle long enough to rot.

00:28:42.020 --> 00:28:45.410
It is hard to look at the coiled
silence of our strongest rope

00:28:45.410 --> 00:28:47.890
and not think of what it has held,

00:28:47.890 --> 00:28:51.210
the heavy grey-green battered
bucket knocking the stone sides

00:28:51.210 --> 00:28:54.260
of the wall, top water
spilling back down,

00:28:54.260 --> 00:28:58.370
this cherished substance
carrying our lives.

00:28:58.370 --> 00:29:03.430
The mare, white and grey, plodding
across the wide open field at dusk,

00:29:03.430 --> 00:29:07.750
her head heavy with labor, the
rope a caress against her cheek,

00:29:07.750 --> 00:29:11.460
the way she turns toward
a gentle tug.

00:29:11.460 --> 00:29:15.630
We hold the balance of
our need in this rope.

00:29:15.630 --> 00:29:22.110
The dead weight of Junebug at
dawn, his skin still steaming,

00:29:22.110 --> 00:29:26.010
his beautiful black skin
catching the morning light,

00:29:26.010 --> 00:29:31.620 position:56%
tender among the leaves, how we
found him there, his neck stretched,

00:29:31.620 --> 00:29:34.370
the wrapping of several
yards of taut rope

00:29:34.370 --> 00:29:39.740
around the drooping branch, where
we found it, how we undid the knot,

00:29:39.740 --> 00:29:43.090
let his body down into
our arms, then carried it

00:29:43.090 --> 00:29:47.380
like a soldier's flag,
bearing it behind the cart,

00:29:47.380 --> 00:29:50.490 position:56%
shaking along with his swollen body.

00:29:50.490 --> 00:29:55.460
This ordinary rope, this
gift we cannot forget,

00:29:55.460 --> 00:30:00.510
this remembrance of
what we have lost.

00:30:00.510 --> 00:30:04.540
Someday a soul will
come out of the fields

00:30:04.540 --> 00:30:08.510 position:56%
to claim it, and then we will know."

00:30:08.510 --> 00:30:10.510
Thank you.

00:30:10.510 --> 00:30:20.240
[ Applause ]

00:30:20.240 --> 00:30:21.540
Thank you.

00:30:21.540 --> 00:30:22.840
&gt;&gt; Angel Batiste: Kwame,
I have a few questions.

00:30:22.840 --> 00:30:24.140
&gt;&gt; Kwame Dawes: A few
questions, good.

00:30:24.140 --> 00:30:28.940
&gt;&gt; Angel Batiste: And each
question has many parts.

00:30:28.940 --> 00:30:38.370
I'd like to start with asking
you wear many hats, actor,

00:30:38.370 --> 00:30:42.490
writer, scholar, musician.

00:30:42.490 --> 00:30:48.640
How did you come into writing?

00:30:48.640 --> 00:30:51.200
&gt;&gt; Kwame Dawes: So these days
I've been sort of rehearsing --

00:30:51.200 --> 00:30:53.960
I've obviously answered
this question before,

00:30:53.960 --> 00:30:57.180
and I realize sometimes
I lie in my answers.

00:30:57.180 --> 00:31:01.560
And then the lie becomes
sort of rigid as truth.

00:31:01.560 --> 00:31:03.740
We see a lot of that.

00:31:03.740 --> 00:31:07.360
So these days I'm -- I've been
forced to re-examine my answers

00:31:07.360 --> 00:31:11.760
to these questions so that I can
speak some truth in all of this.

00:31:11.760 --> 00:31:16.660
It turns out, though, that you
know, writing is a funny thing.

00:31:16.660 --> 00:31:17.960
There are two parts to it.

00:31:17.960 --> 00:31:22.850
One is the motivation to do
it, to actually do the writing.

00:31:22.850 --> 00:31:26.010
The other part is to
feel permission to do it,

00:31:26.010 --> 00:31:28.020
the sense that it's okay to do it.

00:31:28.020 --> 00:31:32.240
And I think some of the struggles
that most writers who are beginning

00:31:32.240 --> 00:31:35.540
to write have is asking themselves,
"Do I have a right to do this?"

00:31:35.540 --> 00:31:40.040
Or, "Do I have -- is it in
-- it doesn't make sense."

00:31:40.040 --> 00:31:44.760
Wives and concerned family
members will say, "What?"

00:31:44.760 --> 00:31:47.330
And they mean it, and
they are not wrong.

00:31:47.330 --> 00:31:50.130
This may not necessarily
be the most --

00:31:50.130 --> 00:31:54.480
the easiest way to eat
on a regular basis.

00:31:54.480 --> 00:31:56.330
So there are those two questions.

00:31:56.330 --> 00:31:59.670
And the other question
is is it in the realm

00:31:59.670 --> 00:32:03.110 position:56%
of possibility as a kind of reality?

00:32:03.110 --> 00:32:08.090
So for the first one, I think it's
safe for me to say that I wrote

00:32:08.090 --> 00:32:11.640
and I write because I read.

00:32:11.640 --> 00:32:16.820
So the business of
reading gave me pleasure.

00:32:16.820 --> 00:32:21.950
And for some -- at some point I
became interested in replicating

00:32:21.950 --> 00:32:25.150
that sensation, and I
discovered that the pleasures

00:32:25.150 --> 00:32:28.060
of reading can be replicated
somehow in writing.

00:32:28.060 --> 00:32:31.920
They are not equivalent,
but they are similar.

00:32:31.920 --> 00:32:36.590
So we grew up in Ghana, and
my father was notoriously

00:32:36.590 --> 00:32:39.510
against television in the '60s.

00:32:39.510 --> 00:32:41.560
So we didn't have a television.

00:32:41.560 --> 00:32:43.000
People did, but we didn't.

00:32:43.000 --> 00:32:44.670
And he was adamant about that.

00:32:44.670 --> 00:32:47.540
I just think he didn't
want to buy a TV,

00:32:47.540 --> 00:32:51.420
but he had wonderful philosophical
reasons for not buying.

00:32:51.420 --> 00:32:54.200
You know, it's market -- he was
a Marxist, so it's capitalist,

00:32:54.200 --> 00:32:57.470
and it's just -- it will addle
your brain, and things like that.

00:32:57.470 --> 00:32:59.970
So -- but what he did
do is that he said,

00:32:59.970 --> 00:33:01.880
"You can buy any book you want.

00:33:01.880 --> 00:33:04.410
And I don't -- I won't
quarrel with that."

00:33:04.410 --> 00:33:08.510
And so -- and this meant comics
even, like you know, Marvel comics.

00:33:08.510 --> 00:33:11.540
Anything that you read,
he said, "That's fine."

00:33:11.540 --> 00:33:18.250
So we just bought comics
[laughter], and he paid for it.

00:33:18.250 --> 00:33:19.550
That's great.

00:33:19.550 --> 00:33:21.240
But -- so we did -- we realized

00:33:21.240 --> 00:33:23.720
that our entertainment would
have to be through reading.

00:33:23.720 --> 00:33:25.360
And so that's what it was.

00:33:25.360 --> 00:33:28.350
And I think soon we as kids --
there were five of us growing up --

00:33:28.350 --> 00:33:31.860
and I think we as kids began to
-- if we ran out of books to read,

00:33:31.860 --> 00:33:34.700
we began to play around
at writing these books.

00:33:34.700 --> 00:33:36.640
We were not precocious
little bright kids.

00:33:36.640 --> 00:33:39.010
We just -- you know,
we -- you know, you go,

00:33:39.010 --> 00:33:41.120
you bully some kids,
you beat them up.

00:33:41.120 --> 00:33:43.350
And then you come home, you
don't have anything to do,

00:33:43.350 --> 00:33:44.650
you don't have a book to read.

00:33:44.650 --> 00:33:46.150
You say, "Hey, let's
make up some stories."

00:33:46.150 --> 00:33:49.290
So it's that -- we were
-- that's what we did.

00:33:49.290 --> 00:33:52.240
Now this doesn't mean all my
family does -- my family --

00:33:52.240 --> 00:33:53.890
I'm the only one who is a writer.

00:33:53.890 --> 00:33:56.210
So that's -- I think
-- but that sense

00:33:56.210 --> 00:34:00.230 position:56%
that I could replicate the sensation
and the pleasures of reading

00:34:00.230 --> 00:34:02.810
through writing started
fairly early.

00:34:02.810 --> 00:34:06.190
And the only other thing that I
think continues to be relevant

00:34:06.190 --> 00:34:11.720
to my impulse to writing is
that when I was about 11, 12,

00:34:11.720 --> 00:34:16.420
maybe about 13, I discovered
this thing called pen pals.

00:34:16.420 --> 00:34:19.880
And in those days there were
these little teen magazines

00:34:19.880 --> 00:34:22.170
that would come, and in
those teen magazines,

00:34:22.170 --> 00:34:26.900 position:56%
at the back of them people from all
over the world would put their names

00:34:26.900 --> 00:34:30.730
and their addresses, and you
could just write a letter to them,

00:34:30.730 --> 00:34:34.570
and you know, you wait three --
well, you wait a month, really,

00:34:34.570 --> 00:34:37.440
maybe a month and a half
-- it's not email --

00:34:37.440 --> 00:34:40.560
and it will come back,
right, with a response.

00:34:40.560 --> 00:34:43.050
And I began to do a
lot of pen pal writing.

00:34:43.050 --> 00:34:48.240 position:56%
And I became kind of drawn to it
because I think it's hard for people

00:34:48.240 --> 00:34:50.500
who are younger to
understand that in a world

00:34:50.500 --> 00:34:56.910 position:56%
in which there is no Internet,
there is no googling of information,

00:34:56.910 --> 00:34:59.720
I could become very quickly,

00:34:59.720 --> 00:35:04.770
at least for the people I was
writing to, the premier authority

00:35:04.770 --> 00:35:07.030
on everything -- not just me,

00:35:07.030 --> 00:35:11.000
but everything Jamaican,
to be honest with you.

00:35:11.000 --> 00:35:15.360
I gain authority because if I
said I like Ackee and saltfish,

00:35:15.360 --> 00:35:17.840
they couldn't google
Ackee and saltfish.

00:35:17.840 --> 00:35:22.520
So if I said Ackee tastes like
-- you know, like ice cream,

00:35:22.520 --> 00:35:25.310
they just had to take
my word for it.

00:35:25.310 --> 00:35:26.770
You understand what I mean.

00:35:26.770 --> 00:35:29.140
But I was -- I became
enamored of this process.

00:35:29.140 --> 00:35:30.940
And I wasn't trying to fake it.

00:35:30.940 --> 00:35:36.340 position:56%
I was trying to -- I found it
exciting that I could bring somebody

00:35:36.340 --> 00:35:39.150 position:56%
into my world and describe my world.

00:35:39.150 --> 00:35:41.730
But I also was seduced by the fact

00:35:41.730 --> 00:35:46.950
that in these letters I became
a protagonist, that I had power,

00:35:46.950 --> 00:35:51.840
that I had a way to manage
narrative and manage experience.

00:35:51.840 --> 00:35:55.680
If I got beat up by somebody,
even in the returning of it,

00:35:55.680 --> 00:35:57.380
even though I was the one beat up,

00:35:57.380 --> 00:35:59.920
I became the heroic
figure in that narrative.

00:35:59.920 --> 00:36:03.430
And this I found deeply
seductive and very attractive.

00:36:03.430 --> 00:36:09.420
And I can't say that that impulse
of writing for the pleasure

00:36:09.420 --> 00:36:14.630
of making words happen for me, and
then writing with the knowledge

00:36:14.630 --> 00:36:17.550
that somebody else is reading
it, and writing with the sense

00:36:17.550 --> 00:36:22.240
that they will return back to me a
response to it, has ever changed.

00:36:22.240 --> 00:36:27.900 position:56%
I think that desire, that
sensation still remains at the heart

00:36:27.900 --> 00:36:32.020
of literally everything that I
do that's pertaining to writing,

00:36:32.020 --> 00:36:34.690
to the theater arts, to
literature, and so on.

00:36:34.690 --> 00:36:37.640 position:56%
So that's a sort of broader picture.

00:36:37.640 --> 00:36:40.430
The step-by-step processes
would be a different thing.

00:36:40.430 --> 00:36:44.980
But I think that's where the
impulse came from and has continued

00:36:44.980 --> 00:36:49.510
until that -- so I'm not the guy
who says, "I write for myself."

00:36:49.510 --> 00:36:52.200
I'm not that guy.

00:36:52.200 --> 00:36:53.500
&gt;&gt; Angel Batiste: Okay.

00:36:53.500 --> 00:36:54.850
&gt;&gt; Kwame Dawes: I don't
understand that guy.

00:36:54.850 --> 00:37:01.050
I think that guy is
lying, frankly, so.

00:37:01.050 --> 00:37:05.790
&gt;&gt; Angel Batiste: I'd like to go
to your work "Natural Mysticism."

00:37:05.790 --> 00:37:12.970
In the work you construct the
concept the Reggae aesthetic.

00:37:12.970 --> 00:37:16.320
What is the Reggae
aesthetic and how has

00:37:16.320 --> 00:37:18.630
that influenced your
writings, your work?

00:37:18.630 --> 00:37:22.110
&gt;&gt; Kwame Dawes: Yeah,
so at some point --

00:37:22.110 --> 00:37:24.160
you know, here's an
interesting story.

00:37:24.160 --> 00:37:29.400
Just recently I've been looking
at diaries I wrote in my 20s.

00:37:29.400 --> 00:37:33.850
And this is one of the beauties
of me saying, "I make up stories

00:37:33.850 --> 00:37:37.470
and think they're true," because
when you read your diary you kind

00:37:37.470 --> 00:37:39.420
of get the facts straightened
out after --

00:37:39.420 --> 00:37:42.060
you know, it's been 30 years
since I've read some of them.

00:37:42.060 --> 00:37:45.120
Well, I always thought
that I started to think

00:37:45.120 --> 00:37:51.990 position:56%
about writing critically about
Reggae when I was a graduate student

00:37:51.990 --> 00:37:57.010
in New Brunswick, which would have
been in the late '80s, '87, '88,

00:37:57.010 --> 00:38:02.740
'89, and that this was something
that I just had started to do then.

00:38:02.740 --> 00:38:06.570
Well, I read a -- I was
reading a diary from 1982,

00:38:06.570 --> 00:38:11.590
and in it I had found some music
-- some Reggae music, and again,

00:38:11.590 --> 00:38:16.590
you have to understand at the
time if you didn't have the record

00:38:16.590 --> 00:38:19.540
or the tape, you didn't
have the music.

00:38:19.540 --> 00:38:22.200
You had to get the actual thing.

00:38:22.200 --> 00:38:25.370
And somebody had given me a
whole bunch of Bob Marley tapes.

00:38:25.370 --> 00:38:27.050
Even though I grew up
listening to Bob Marley,

00:38:27.050 --> 00:38:31.320
there were songs I didn't know that
he had done, which predated me.

00:38:31.320 --> 00:38:34.130
And I started to -- and I
wrote about it in the diary.

00:38:34.130 --> 00:38:37.850
I started to do this analysis
of the lyrics and so on.

00:38:37.850 --> 00:38:39.770
And then I said, "One
of these days I'm going

00:38:39.770 --> 00:38:41.270
to write a book about Bob Marley."

00:38:41.270 --> 00:38:45.450
This is what I wrote in 1982.

00:38:45.450 --> 00:38:46.900
Just, you know, that comment.

00:38:46.900 --> 00:38:50.040
And the book, "Bob Marley,
Lyrical Genius," which came

00:38:50.040 --> 00:38:55.210
out in the 2000s, came from that
initial impulse, which it struck me

00:38:55.210 --> 00:38:58.090
as like shocking that I was
thinking in those lines.

00:38:58.090 --> 00:39:00.970
But part of the reason is that when
I started to think about writing,

00:39:00.970 --> 00:39:03.640
and when I started to think
of myself as a writer,

00:39:03.640 --> 00:39:06.370
I wanted to understand
a kind of aesthetic

00:39:06.370 --> 00:39:13.010
that resisted the inclination
toward a kind of slavish dependence

00:39:13.010 --> 00:39:17.590
on Western ideologies, and Western
literature, and Western culture.

00:39:17.590 --> 00:39:20.790
And a number of voices
began to help me to do that.

00:39:20.790 --> 00:39:24.830
And one was Amiri Baraka
talking about Blues people.

00:39:24.830 --> 00:39:27.120
The other was Karlamu Gya
Salaam [assumed spelling],

00:39:27.120 --> 00:39:28.920
who has written brilliantly
about the Blues.

00:39:28.920 --> 00:39:31.180
And the other, of course,
was Langston Hughes writing

00:39:31.180 --> 00:39:33.460
about the Blues in "Negro
Artist and the Racial Mountain."

00:39:33.460 --> 00:39:36.330
I became fascinated
with their try --

00:39:36.330 --> 00:39:40.510
attempt to create a
vernacular for black poetics.

00:39:40.510 --> 00:39:44.520
And I thought, "This is
confidence-building," because one

00:39:44.520 --> 00:39:47.370
of the things that damages
you sometimes as a writer is

00:39:47.370 --> 00:39:49.700
when you start asking
yourself, "Who am I?

00:39:49.700 --> 00:39:51.000
And who are my people?

00:39:51.000 --> 00:39:52.300
And where am I from?"

00:39:52.300 --> 00:39:54.350 position:56%
And I mean that in a literary sense.

00:39:54.350 --> 00:39:56.760
So I thought, "This is attractive,
and this is interesting."

00:39:56.760 --> 00:40:00.470
Then I watched Kamau Brathwaite,
who is a great Caribbean poet,

00:40:00.470 --> 00:40:03.760
invoke jazz as a functioning
kind of aesthetic.

00:40:03.760 --> 00:40:07.940
And I realized that he wasn't
entirely happy with that invocation

00:40:07.940 --> 00:40:11.150
because it was borrowing something
from African American culture,

00:40:11.150 --> 00:40:15.010
which he felt okay with, but he
was also wrestling to see what

00:40:15.010 --> 00:40:17.310 position:56%
in the Caribbean would speak to him.

00:40:17.310 --> 00:40:21.540
So he began to develop this idea
of a kind of jazz aesthetic,

00:40:21.540 --> 00:40:22.840
which I found very interesting.

00:40:22.840 --> 00:40:24.530
And I started to read up on jazz.

00:40:24.530 --> 00:40:25.830
And I thought, "This is cool.

00:40:25.830 --> 00:40:28.090
You know, you have a
kind of folk aesthetic,

00:40:28.090 --> 00:40:29.960
a kind of populist aesthetic

00:40:29.960 --> 00:40:32.300
that you can then create
a poetics out of it."

00:40:32.300 --> 00:40:37.170
And then I read Nicolas Guillen,
using sun music in Cuba to try

00:40:37.170 --> 00:40:41.600
and explain the sort of Afrocentric
nature of his poetics, and so on.

00:40:41.600 --> 00:40:44.680
And then, of course, I
started to look at Yeats.

00:40:44.680 --> 00:40:46.020
And I thought, "Yeats
is interesting."

00:40:46.020 --> 00:40:47.360
And I realized there's
a whole period

00:40:47.360 --> 00:40:49.280
of Yeats' work which
is anti-British.

00:40:49.280 --> 00:40:51.550
By the way, it's just the British
that you had a problem with,

00:40:51.550 --> 00:40:55.690
not anybody else, because
[inaudible] such a big influence.

00:40:55.690 --> 00:40:58.580
You know, Derek Walcott, divided
and [inaudible] and all that.

00:40:58.580 --> 00:41:02.040
So say it's a big and
lasting influence.

00:41:02.040 --> 00:41:05.670
And I found those things exciting,
so then I started to ask myself,

00:41:05.670 --> 00:41:09.130
"What is the space --
what is the aesthetic

00:41:09.130 --> 00:41:12.450
and emotional space
that I'm growing up in?"

00:41:12.450 --> 00:41:16.890 position:56%
And I realized that Reggae music and
all that it meant in the late '60s

00:41:16.890 --> 00:41:19.580
and early '70s was
defining who I was.

00:41:19.580 --> 00:41:24.330 position:56%
And in fact, I began to see in poets
like Lorna Goodison, Mervyn Morris,

00:41:24.330 --> 00:41:25.710
all these Jamaican poets,

00:41:25.710 --> 00:41:28.410
a clear sense in which they
were being influenced by Reggae,

00:41:28.410 --> 00:41:32.060 position:56%
without admitting it, without even
saying, "This is what has happened."

00:41:32.060 --> 00:41:34.690
So that brought me to this
scholarly idea that I want

00:41:34.690 --> 00:41:38.690 position:56%
to investigate whether there is such
a thing that one could construct

00:41:38.690 --> 00:41:42.280
as a Reggae aesthetic through the
Aristotelian approach of saying,

00:41:42.280 --> 00:41:44.270
"Let me look at the text
and see if I can see

00:41:44.270 --> 00:41:48.780
in the text those aesthetic
lines that make sense."

00:41:48.780 --> 00:41:52.360
And it began to hold
together very well for me.

00:41:52.360 --> 00:41:56.080
And so the book, "Natural
Mysticism," became a way

00:41:56.080 --> 00:42:00.220
in which I began to look at
whether, in fact, this phenomenon

00:42:00.220 --> 00:42:04.780 position:56%
of Reggae music with its antecedents
being, you know, Kumina and all

00:42:04.780 --> 00:42:08.700
of these Afrocentric
music styles, was in fact,

00:42:08.700 --> 00:42:11.420
shaping a poetics in the Caribbean.

00:42:11.420 --> 00:42:14.630
And then I realized it was
also shaping my own poetics.

00:42:14.630 --> 00:42:17.790
So the Reggae aesthetic
is not prescriptive.

00:42:17.790 --> 00:42:19.090
It's descriptive.

00:42:19.090 --> 00:42:21.410
It's actually saying,
"This is what has happened,

00:42:21.410 --> 00:42:24.290
and I'm very interested
in seeing how it evolves"

00:42:24.290 --> 00:42:26.430
And then recognizing
those elements in myself.

00:42:26.430 --> 00:42:32.550 position:56%
But even as it's descriptive, it's
also incredibly confidence-endowing.

00:42:32.550 --> 00:42:37.210
It makes you feel like you are
coming from a credible space

00:42:37.210 --> 00:42:42.230
that comes out of this wonderful
complexity of cultures mixing

00:42:42.230 --> 00:42:45.720
and creating something, as Kamau
Brathwaite says, torn and new.

00:42:45.720 --> 00:42:47.930
So Africa makes senses
in the Caribbean.

00:42:47.930 --> 00:42:52.320 position:56%
Africa makes sense in South Carolina
in the Gullah people and so on.

00:42:52.320 --> 00:42:54.800
All of that begins to
make sense and works

00:42:54.800 --> 00:42:59.400
within this musical form called
Reggae in very complex ways.

00:42:59.400 --> 00:43:02.010
So I could -- this is one topic
I could go on and on forever

00:43:02.010 --> 00:43:07.690
about because, of course, it
does go on and on forever, yeah.

00:43:07.690 --> 00:43:11.450
&gt;&gt; Angel Batiste: I'd like
to ask one question in terms

00:43:11.450 --> 00:43:16.960
of this concept, is this an
extension, or does it extend

00:43:16.960 --> 00:43:18.870
into the Pan-African aesthetic?

00:43:18.870 --> 00:43:20.650
Or is there Pan-African aesthetic.

00:43:20.650 --> 00:43:22.680
&gt;&gt; Kwame Dawes: Yeah, it's
absolutely an extension.

00:43:22.680 --> 00:43:26.770
So one of the interesting things
that I've been very fascinated

00:43:26.770 --> 00:43:30.050
about is, for instance,
Rastafarianism.

00:43:30.050 --> 00:43:34.880
Rastafarianism started, really,
we date it to 1938, right?

00:43:34.880 --> 00:43:37.280
1936, '37, '38.

00:43:37.280 --> 00:43:40.440
We can actually tell when
this new religion started.

00:43:40.440 --> 00:43:42.340
But the thing is, so
we talk about Rasta

00:43:42.340 --> 00:43:44.390
as this new religion
that just starts.

00:43:44.390 --> 00:43:48.700
And Rasta's fundamental premise
is that it looks to Africa --

00:43:48.700 --> 00:43:52.820
it presumes an important
line, shared --

00:43:52.820 --> 00:43:57.950
given to it by gesture by
somebody like Haile Selassie.

00:43:57.950 --> 00:43:59.480
Haile Selassie comes in and says --

00:43:59.480 --> 00:44:02.510
you know, he takes the title
Conquering Lion of the Tribe

00:44:02.510 --> 00:44:06.420
of Judah, takes the title that in
the -- in sort of the narrative --

00:44:06.420 --> 00:44:10.210
the mythic narrative that he
comes from the tribe of David,

00:44:10.210 --> 00:44:12.530
he comes from the Queen
of Sheba, and so on.

00:44:12.530 --> 00:44:14.690
And Rastas then say,
"Okay, here's this.

00:44:14.690 --> 00:44:16.090
This is interesting.

00:44:16.090 --> 00:44:20.850
So we then see Haile Selassie
as the returned messiah."

00:44:20.850 --> 00:44:26.180
So the Rastas then construct a
kind of belief system around that,

00:44:26.180 --> 00:44:29.730
but it's a radical political belief
system, because what it's doing is

00:44:29.730 --> 00:44:33.580
that it's proposing
that God is black.

00:44:33.580 --> 00:44:36.370
This is problematic for
other people, but --

00:44:36.370 --> 00:44:40.610
but the question then becomes,
"Well, why are you panicking?

00:44:40.610 --> 00:44:44.220
I thought you said God -- doesn't
matter -- race doesn't matter?"

00:44:44.220 --> 00:44:47.460 position:56%
But when suddenly God, the returned
messiah is black and kind of hanging

00:44:47.460 --> 00:44:51.800
out in Ethiopia, this complicates
the conversation, right?

00:44:51.800 --> 00:44:54.180
And it's not madness at all.

00:44:54.180 --> 00:44:57.380
It's actually a profoundly
reasonable argument

00:44:57.380 --> 00:45:01.850
that proposes a discourse that says
those who have shown the capacity

00:45:01.850 --> 00:45:06.540
to resist colonialism, resist
Babylon, resist the oppression

00:45:06.540 --> 00:45:09.340
of African people,
and look attractive

00:45:09.340 --> 00:45:14.420 position:56%
and make sense ideologically as a
part of a functioning belief system.

00:45:14.420 --> 00:45:16.960
So Rasta emerges as this entity.

00:45:16.960 --> 00:45:18.950
And there's a long story
about how it develops.

00:45:18.950 --> 00:45:21.040 position:56%
But sometimes the mistake we make is

00:45:21.040 --> 00:45:23.940
that Rasta just fell
down out of the sky.

00:45:23.940 --> 00:45:27.700
But if you look at the
antecedents of Rasta,

00:45:27.700 --> 00:45:31.560
just think of the simple Negro
spiritual, "Go down Moses,

00:45:31.560 --> 00:45:35.100
way down in Egypt land, tell
old Pharaoh let my people go."

00:45:35.100 --> 00:45:40.130
Built into that narrative,
that song, is a reconstruction

00:45:40.130 --> 00:45:45.930
of Christianity, because
Moses is claiming to be --

00:45:45.930 --> 00:45:51.110
the black people -- he -- the black
people are the children of Israel.

00:45:51.110 --> 00:45:57.140
They're the chosen people, which
makes the white people not,

00:45:57.140 --> 00:46:01.370 position:56%
which is a radical kind of thinking.

00:46:01.370 --> 00:46:07.860 position:56%
And that radical kind of thinking is
a creative invention that is there

00:46:07.860 --> 00:46:12.960 position:56%
for resistance, as a way to resist
and a way to bring a moral authority

00:46:12.960 --> 00:46:16.530
on the actions of those who
claim to have a kind of control

00:46:16.530 --> 00:46:18.210
and authority over that action.

00:46:18.210 --> 00:46:20.390
And I think there is
a way in which --

00:46:20.390 --> 00:46:24.460
and the truth is, Jamaica's
resistance movements,

00:46:24.460 --> 00:46:28.660
the Morant Bay rebellion and so on,
all were influenced by Baptists.

00:46:28.660 --> 00:46:32.680
And those Baptists were
formed in the early 1800s

00:46:32.680 --> 00:46:38.240
by African American ex-slaves who
escaped, and moved to Jamaica,

00:46:38.240 --> 00:46:41.200
and started the Baptist
movement in Jamaica.

00:46:41.200 --> 00:46:46.650
So this Rasta movement comes out --
this Africa is all the way through,

00:46:46.650 --> 00:46:51.560
this notion that the
African Americans, and so on,

00:46:51.560 --> 00:46:53.180
so forth, this is a myth.

00:46:53.180 --> 00:46:56.350
So for me, that long
narrative begins

00:46:56.350 --> 00:47:00.740
to make sense in that cyclical way.

00:47:00.740 --> 00:47:04.230
And so Reggae aesthetic
does have an antecedent.

00:47:04.230 --> 00:47:10.000 position:56%
It has an antecedent that connects
with other movements that are trying

00:47:10.000 --> 00:47:12.490
to reclaim a cultural identity

00:47:12.490 --> 00:47:15.630
and a cultural sensibility both
politically, ideologically,

00:47:15.630 --> 00:47:18.590
spiritually, in language, and
all these kinds of things.

00:47:18.590 --> 00:47:22.780
And I'm not even a Rasta.

00:47:22.780 --> 00:47:24.080
Do you understand?

00:47:24.080 --> 00:47:25.380
But I own that.

00:47:25.380 --> 00:47:29.210
I -- it's part of my
understanding of it, yeah.

00:47:29.210 --> 00:47:30.510
&gt;&gt; Angel Batiste: Thank you.

00:47:30.510 --> 00:47:34.680
Let's go on and talk a
bit about your new series,

00:47:34.680 --> 00:47:40.560
"New Generation African Poets,"
which you edit with Chris Abani.

00:47:40.560 --> 00:47:48.340 position:56%
You're featuring eight new, emerging
African poets in this series?

00:47:48.340 --> 00:47:51.190
&gt;&gt; Kwame Dawes: Well, the series
is an interesting project.

00:47:51.190 --> 00:47:55.670
It's a proposal that we -- that I
came up with about three years ago.

00:47:55.670 --> 00:48:01.400
And the proposal was that for
10 years we will publish eight

00:48:01.400 --> 00:48:06.440
to 10 chapbooks of African poets --

00:48:06.440 --> 00:48:10.900
new generation, poets who have not
been published in book form before.

00:48:10.900 --> 00:48:12.960
And we do that once a year.

00:48:12.960 --> 00:48:15.380
So we are now -- next year
we bring on the fourth one.

00:48:15.380 --> 00:48:16.740
So we do one every year.

00:48:16.740 --> 00:48:19.350
So we started one three year ago.

00:48:19.350 --> 00:48:21.720
And so far we've been
doing it steadily, easily.

00:48:21.720 --> 00:48:23.200
So this is the first one.

00:48:23.200 --> 00:48:26.750
This was a -- this
one had seven, right.

00:48:26.750 --> 00:48:28.050
Okay, good.

00:48:28.050 --> 00:48:29.530
That -- you can see
them, the covers.

00:48:29.530 --> 00:48:32.320
And this is the third
one -- or the second one.

00:48:32.320 --> 00:48:35.200
And I think we had -- I can't call.

00:48:35.200 --> 00:48:37.260
This is probably eight in this one.

00:48:37.260 --> 00:48:45.300
And then more recently,
we did this one.

00:48:45.300 --> 00:48:47.190
So this is another eight.

00:48:47.190 --> 00:48:49.120
So this is the one that
you are referring to.

00:48:49.120 --> 00:48:51.740
And then next year's is
going to have 10 poets.

00:48:51.740 --> 00:48:54.620 position:56%
So it's going to vary in that sense.

00:48:54.620 --> 00:48:57.570
But these are new writers
who haven't been published,

00:48:57.570 --> 00:49:00.840
and we do a chapbook for
each one of them each year.

00:49:00.840 --> 00:49:05.260
And the idea is that in 10 years'
time we would have published 90

00:49:05.260 --> 00:49:07.740
to 100 new poets from Africa.

00:49:07.740 --> 00:49:11.210
Of the first set -- that
is the first box set --

00:49:11.210 --> 00:49:14.280
the first and second box
set, all but a couple

00:49:14.280 --> 00:49:17.700 position:56%
of those poets have already either
have contracts for full-length book,

00:49:17.700 --> 00:49:21.410
or they have full-length books
already published as a result

00:49:21.410 --> 00:49:24.080
of the attention that
these works [inaudible].

00:49:24.080 --> 00:49:26.490
Essentially we've decided
to use this mechanism

00:49:26.490 --> 00:49:29.270
to start changing the landscape
of publishing for African poets,

00:49:29.270 --> 00:49:32.940
and to make sure that African
poet will be published.

00:49:32.940 --> 00:49:34.380
And this sounds like a lot,

00:49:34.380 --> 00:49:37.040
but Africa is a big
place, you know, and stuff.

00:49:37.040 --> 00:49:38.390
It's a big continent.

00:49:38.390 --> 00:49:41.460
To do eight a year is like
scratching the surface.

00:49:41.460 --> 00:49:44.400
I mean, you're barely -- we're
barely scratching the surface.

00:49:44.400 --> 00:49:47.770
&gt;&gt; Angel Batiste: Is there a reason
that you chose the chapbook format?

00:49:47.770 --> 00:49:50.770
&gt;&gt; Kwame Dawes: Yeah, so
we've decided to approach this

00:49:50.770 --> 00:49:53.800
on a multipronged way,
so we're doing chapbooks,

00:49:53.800 --> 00:49:57.850
but we're also doing a series
called "A Classic Series"

00:49:57.850 --> 00:50:02.020
by major African poets who have
been published already, and so on

00:50:02.020 --> 00:50:05.160
and so forth, who do not
have a collected poems

00:50:05.160 --> 00:50:06.710
or a major new and selected poems.

00:50:06.710 --> 00:50:09.640
And so we started with
Kofi Awoonor's book.

00:50:09.640 --> 00:50:12.870
And that was a collected poems.

00:50:12.870 --> 00:50:17.510
And then we followed that up
with Gabriel Okara from Nigeria,

00:50:17.510 --> 00:50:20.270
a major -- one of the
first major poets

00:50:20.270 --> 00:50:22.060
from Africa, who is still living.

00:50:22.060 --> 00:50:25.210
And so we've done a
collected poems of his.

00:50:25.210 --> 00:50:28.440
And then we are bringing out next
year Amate Alu's [assumed spelling]

00:50:28.440 --> 00:50:29.790
collected poems.

00:50:29.790 --> 00:50:31.940
Amate published two
collections of poems,

00:50:31.940 --> 00:50:35.490 position:56%
but had written multiple collections
of poems that were never published.

00:50:35.490 --> 00:50:37.330
So we did the work to
pull that together.

00:50:37.330 --> 00:50:39.400 position:56%
And so her book comes out next year.

00:50:39.400 --> 00:50:40.700
And then each year it will be --

00:50:40.700 --> 00:50:42.360
and then the following year
Keo Pitser [assumed spelling],

00:50:42.360 --> 00:50:45.600
who has been here before, we'll be
publishing his new and selected.

00:50:45.600 --> 00:50:48.110
So that's one series
that we do, one a year.

00:50:48.110 --> 00:50:51.550
And then we have a book prize
for the -- first book prize --

00:50:51.550 --> 00:50:54.200
full-length book prize for
African poets called the Sillerman

00:50:54.200 --> 00:50:55.500
Book Prize.

00:50:55.500 --> 00:50:56.800
And we publish that volume.

00:50:56.800 --> 00:50:59.850
And then we have an
over-the-transom series where poets

00:50:59.850 --> 00:51:01.920
who may have published
before -- they're, you know,

00:51:01.920 --> 00:51:04.370
established poets --
can send manuscripts in,

00:51:04.370 --> 00:51:06.460
and we will, you know, publish it.

00:51:06.460 --> 00:51:08.370
We'll arrange for them to
be published, and so on.

00:51:08.370 --> 00:51:12.740
So it's a multi-pronged
publishing sort of effort.

00:51:12.740 --> 00:51:14.810
Even though we -- when
I say we publish it,

00:51:14.810 --> 00:51:19.160
what we do is we broker the
publication of these books, yeah.

00:51:19.160 --> 00:51:23.130
&gt;&gt; Angel Batiste: Now with this
new generation of African poets,

00:51:23.130 --> 00:51:26.600
what are some of the
themes, subjects?

00:51:26.600 --> 00:51:30.620
&gt;&gt; Kwame Dawes: Yeah, so I think
what we -- what I've tried to do --

00:51:30.620 --> 00:51:33.830
they -- you know, I'm an
academic and a scholar.

00:51:33.830 --> 00:51:35.650
And my training is that way.

00:51:35.650 --> 00:51:38.290
And so my inclination is
to do that, is to say,

00:51:38.290 --> 00:51:40.000
"This is what is going on.

00:51:40.000 --> 00:51:42.090
Let me write a book about
that," and so on and so forth.

00:51:42.090 --> 00:51:46.650 position:56%
But I've had to sort of resist that
as an editor, to even think about it

00:51:46.650 --> 00:51:50.580
in those terms, because I
want the work to emerge,

00:51:50.580 --> 00:51:52.310
and then to start speaking itself.

00:51:52.310 --> 00:51:54.770
But of course, for each
of the box sets we have

00:51:54.770 --> 00:51:56.070
to write an introduction.

00:51:56.070 --> 00:51:59.460 position:56%
So when I come to write the
introduction, I start to see themes.

00:51:59.460 --> 00:52:01.560
One of the most striking
themes that I'm seeing --

00:52:01.560 --> 00:52:06.690
first of all, the next boxed set
of the 10 poets, nine are women.

00:52:06.690 --> 00:52:09.900
This is what has happened.

00:52:09.900 --> 00:52:13.320 position:56%
And in my introduction -- the
introduction that Chris and I wrote,

00:52:13.320 --> 00:52:17.130
we kept returning to this idea
of the body, the female body,

00:52:17.130 --> 00:52:20.380
the African woman's body, the
way that the body is read the way

00:52:20.380 --> 00:52:24.800
that the body is resistant, the
way that that body is trying

00:52:24.800 --> 00:52:27.920
to understand itself
in a changing world.

00:52:27.920 --> 00:52:29.350
And keep in mind that
these are poets

00:52:29.350 --> 00:52:31.220
from all different
countries in Africa.

00:52:31.220 --> 00:52:32.610
Some are in the diaspora.

00:52:32.610 --> 00:52:34.030
Some are living in Sweden.

00:52:34.030 --> 00:52:35.330
Some are living in Britain.

00:52:35.330 --> 00:52:36.730
Some are living here in America.

00:52:36.730 --> 00:52:39.940
So they -- you see the
influence of migration.

00:52:39.940 --> 00:52:46.300
You see the influence of a global
sensibility, the communication

00:52:46.300 --> 00:52:48.690
that the Internet has created.

00:52:48.690 --> 00:52:51.250
You see the influence
of them reading works

00:52:51.250 --> 00:52:53.220
from different places, and so on.

00:52:53.220 --> 00:52:57.260
But what is consistent all the way
through is that they self-identify

00:52:57.260 --> 00:53:02.080
as African bodies that are
trying to negotiate what

00:53:02.080 --> 00:53:04.360
that means in a global landscape.

00:53:04.360 --> 00:53:06.450
I think that is a consistent theme

00:53:06.450 --> 00:53:08.880
that we see running
through these works.

00:53:08.880 --> 00:53:10.660
&gt;&gt; Angel Batiste: The
cover illustration on all

00:53:10.660 --> 00:53:13.040
of these books are
absolutely beautiful.

00:53:13.040 --> 00:53:14.990
&gt;&gt; Kwame Dawes: Yeah, you know
the story behind these, right?

00:53:14.990 --> 00:53:19.160
So what we decided to do, for
every box set we get one artist.

00:53:19.160 --> 00:53:23.380
We get a major African artist,
and we ask them to supply art

00:53:23.380 --> 00:53:24.680
for each one of the covers.

00:53:24.680 --> 00:53:28.030
So it's a single artist
for each of these box sets.

00:53:28.030 --> 00:53:30.940
So this is a wonderful
Nigerian artist who --

00:53:30.940 --> 00:53:33.280
so all the covers are
from his artwork.

00:53:33.280 --> 00:53:35.080
And we have a lot of
Nigerian artists.

00:53:35.080 --> 00:53:37.080
The first one is a Nigerian artist.

00:53:37.080 --> 00:53:42.850
And then this year,
[inaudible] you know,

00:53:42.850 --> 00:53:48.200
Elizabeth Alexander's husband --
late husband, who is from Somalia,

00:53:48.200 --> 00:53:53.080
or [inaudible] originally,
he's -- she gave us his work.

00:53:53.080 --> 00:53:54.970
So that is featured on
