00:53:59.430 --> 00:54:03.270
And I just think that's cool.

00:54:03.270 --> 00:54:06.790
I don't know about you, but
I think that's really cool.

00:54:06.790 --> 00:54:08.090 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Angel Batiste: They're beautiful.

00:54:08.090 --> 00:54:09.420
&gt;&gt; Kwame Dawes: Right, and
they give it to us free.

00:54:09.420 --> 00:54:10.720
We don't have to pay for it.

00:54:10.720 --> 00:54:12.020
That's generosity.

00:54:12.020 --> 00:54:14.620
Now we should, but we
can't afford to pay for it.

00:54:14.620 --> 00:54:16.300
So they -- yeah.

00:54:16.300 --> 00:54:20.380 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Angel Batiste: My next question
-- and it might be a bit repetitive.

00:54:20.380 --> 00:54:21.680
&gt;&gt; Kwame Dawes: That's okay.

00:54:21.680 --> 00:54:23.070
&gt;&gt; Angel Batiste: But
in terms of as Editor

00:54:23.070 --> 00:54:26.520
of the African Poetry Book Fund,

00:54:26.520 --> 00:54:29.820
what is really the history
of the organization?

00:54:29.820 --> 00:54:33.540
What are some of the long-term
goals of the organization?

00:54:33.540 --> 00:54:37.040
&gt;&gt; Kwame Dawes: Yeah, so the
African Poetry Book Fund begins

00:54:37.040 --> 00:54:44.580
through a series of circumstances
that have to do with recognizing

00:54:44.580 --> 00:54:48.980 position:56%
and absence, a gap in thinking, that
something has to be done about it.

00:54:48.980 --> 00:54:54.440
Chris Abani and I were touring
in Africa for the -- there's a --

00:54:54.440 --> 00:54:59.360
Poetry Africa is a wonderful
festival that happens every year,

00:54:59.360 --> 00:55:02.650
and they brought us there
to tour Southern Africa.

00:55:02.650 --> 00:55:05.050
So we were visiting a few places.

00:55:05.050 --> 00:55:06.990
And we were struck by
a couple of things.

00:55:06.990 --> 00:55:10.260
One is there are so many
wonderful poets who were performing

00:55:10.260 --> 00:55:13.850
and doing good work, but they
hadn't opportunity to publish.

00:55:13.850 --> 00:55:17.220
We also saw a lot of work that
needed mentoring, needed editing,

00:55:17.220 --> 00:55:20.840
needed some clear attention,
and they were not getting it.

00:55:20.840 --> 00:55:24.310 position:56%
And we started to make relationships
with poets to meet them,

00:55:24.310 --> 00:55:27.360
talk to them about it, and
to talk about opportunities.

00:55:27.360 --> 00:55:31.400
Many of them were publishing, but
didn't know where to send works

00:55:31.400 --> 00:55:33.560
to journals and things like that.

00:55:33.560 --> 00:55:37.600
They were rightly concerned that if
they sent it to American journals,

00:55:37.600 --> 00:55:40.650
they would just be dismissed,
and not understood, and so on.

00:55:40.650 --> 00:55:42.780
So we started to talk
with them about that.

00:55:42.780 --> 00:55:45.130
So then eventually in our
conversations we thought,

00:55:45.130 --> 00:55:49.480
"Why don't we find a way to
start publishing these works?

00:55:49.480 --> 00:55:51.620
And to arrange to publish
these works?"

00:55:51.620 --> 00:55:55.620
Now I have a history of
creating opportunities

00:55:55.620 --> 00:55:57.970
for the publication of work.

00:55:57.970 --> 00:56:01.040
In South Carolina, for
many years the University

00:56:01.040 --> 00:56:03.930
of South Carolina Press decided
not to publish poetry again

00:56:03.930 --> 00:56:08.230
after starting the James Dickey
series, which didn't go well.

00:56:08.230 --> 00:56:10.830
And so they decided against it.

00:56:10.830 --> 00:56:12.470
So I approached them,
and I wanted to --

00:56:12.470 --> 00:56:16.220 position:56%
I started an organization called
the South Carolina Poetry Initiative

00:56:16.220 --> 00:56:19.320
to do -- to publish work and
to promote the work of poetry

00:56:19.320 --> 00:56:21.660
in South Carolina for everybody.

00:56:21.660 --> 00:56:22.960
And I approached them, and I said,

00:56:22.960 --> 00:56:25.600 position:56%
"Why don't you guys start publishing
poetry, because, you know,

00:56:25.600 --> 00:56:27.430
we've got some good poets here?"

00:56:27.430 --> 00:56:29.350
And they said, "No,
it's just a bad idea.

00:56:29.350 --> 00:56:30.670
It's dangerous, and so on.

00:56:30.670 --> 00:56:32.810
Nobody buys poetry, and so on."

00:56:32.810 --> 00:56:34.590
So then I sought funding.

00:56:34.590 --> 00:56:39.100
I looked for money, and I said,
"Look, I'll give you the money

00:56:39.100 --> 00:56:42.330
to subvent the cost of publication
so you don't lose any money."

00:56:42.330 --> 00:56:44.010
So that excuse goes out the window.

00:56:44.010 --> 00:56:46.750
And they said, "Well, we don't
know where we'll find the poets."

00:56:46.750 --> 00:56:48.050
I said, "Well, we'll find them."

00:56:48.050 --> 00:56:50.360
And then they said, "Well, we
don't have a poetry editor."

00:56:50.360 --> 00:56:52.700
And I said, "I will edit it.

00:56:52.700 --> 00:56:55.240
And we'll get it edited, and
then we'll work with you,

00:56:55.240 --> 00:56:57.450
and we'll publish these
books, and so on."

00:56:57.450 --> 00:57:00.430
Now there is such a thing called
the Palmetto Poetry Series

00:57:00.430 --> 00:57:02.860
in South Carolina that
is still going strong.

00:57:02.860 --> 00:57:04.160
