01:01:12.060 --> 01:01:18.080
It's been very helpful.

01:01:18.080 --> 01:01:19.380
Yeah.

01:01:19.380 --> 01:01:24.180 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Angel Batiste: Working with both,
working with the African Poetry Fan

01:01:24.180 --> 01:01:32.450 position:56%
and Prairie Schooner, how do you see
African poetry and American poetry?

01:01:32.450 --> 01:01:34.810
Is there a contrast?

01:01:34.810 --> 01:01:37.500
Are their comparisons?

01:01:37.500 --> 01:01:41.600
Is there something that
can be lent to each other?

01:01:41.600 --> 01:01:43.470
&gt;&gt; Kwame Dawes: I think
that's a good question,

01:01:43.470 --> 01:01:44.970
but you know what,
here's the problem.

01:01:44.970 --> 01:01:50.330
I think -- I have to say that is a
profound compromise that I'm doing

01:01:50.330 --> 01:01:54.070
when I say things like
African poetry.

01:01:54.070 --> 01:01:56.340
Because in a sense,
that's a bit of misnomer.

01:01:56.340 --> 01:01:58.080
It's a convenience.

01:01:58.080 --> 01:02:00.830
It's a convenience
because of colonialism.

01:02:00.830 --> 01:02:03.860
It's a convenience
because we totalize Africa

01:02:03.860 --> 01:02:05.420
as if it's one place.

01:02:05.420 --> 01:02:09.610
And we do it because it's the
only way people understand.

01:02:09.610 --> 01:02:12.540
If I said it's Nigerian
poetry, with a population

01:02:12.540 --> 01:02:14.740
of almost 200 million
people, people will say, well,

01:02:14.740 --> 01:02:16.240
that's a little parochial.

01:02:16.240 --> 01:02:17.540
You understand what I mean?

01:02:17.540 --> 01:02:20.930
So there's a way in which we
have to speak in a language

01:02:20.930 --> 01:02:24.590
that people will understand
to get the thing done.

01:02:24.590 --> 01:02:30.570
So comparing African poetry with
American poetry is a bit wonky.

01:02:30.570 --> 01:02:34.370
The reason I say that is American
poetry is more homogenous,

01:02:34.370 --> 01:02:36.510 position:56%
even though it's complex and varied.

01:02:36.510 --> 01:02:39.900
But if you think about all the
thousands of language groups

01:02:39.900 --> 01:02:42.350
in Africa, all the
different tribes in Africa,

01:02:42.350 --> 01:02:46.730 position:56%
all the different literal nations in
Africa, to collect them as one thing

01:02:46.730 --> 01:02:49.520
and say one thing about
it is, I think --

01:02:49.520 --> 01:02:54.350
it's actually misleading and
intellectually problematic.

01:02:54.350 --> 01:02:58.340
Which is why when people ask me
let's talk about African poetry,

01:02:58.340 --> 01:03:01.940
I'm resistant of sort of
making broad generalizations

01:03:01.940 --> 01:03:05.140
because I think it
perpetuates this myth

01:03:05.140 --> 01:03:08.790
that African poetry is one
thing or looks like one thing,

01:03:08.790 --> 01:03:11.610
in the very same way that,
frankly, if you were honest

01:03:11.610 --> 01:03:14.800
and somebody said, "Tell us about
American poetry," you would go,

01:03:14.800 --> 01:03:17.090
"I don't know what the
heck you're talking about."

01:03:17.090 --> 01:03:23.510
Like, how do you put somebody --
Billy Collins behind Ameri Baraka?

01:03:23.510 --> 01:03:24.810
I mean, what connects them?

01:03:24.810 --> 01:03:27.650
And all we do is run to Walt
Whitman and Emily Dickinson

01:03:27.650 --> 01:03:30.840
and say that's the root
and that's all we can do.

01:03:30.840 --> 01:03:32.140
You understand?

01:03:32.140 --> 01:03:35.900 position:56%
And everybody does this, as if this
is the only answer to that question.

01:03:35.900 --> 01:03:39.020
So that's one kind of the answer.

01:03:39.020 --> 01:03:45.480
But the other part of the answer
is to say that America has grown

01:03:45.480 --> 01:03:49.980
and its poetry has grown and
blossomed because of its openness

01:03:49.980 --> 01:03:51.830
to poetry from other
parts of the world.

01:03:51.830 --> 01:03:57.170
And that openness has come through
publication and through translation

01:03:57.170 --> 01:03:59.350
and through communication.

01:03:59.350 --> 01:04:02.190
And that's why us doing this

01:04:02.190 --> 01:04:05.370
with African poetry
enriches American poetry.

01:04:05.370 --> 01:04:08.840
It gives America access
to the poetics of a place

01:04:08.840 --> 01:04:13.570
that it has ignored for so
long, sometimes not willfully

01:04:13.570 --> 01:04:15.960
because there's just not
enough books for them to look

01:04:15.960 --> 01:04:19.290
at to see what the connections
are and to create a conversation.

01:04:19.290 --> 01:04:23.020
So indeed, I think it
enriches the American --

01:04:23.020 --> 01:04:25.310
because it challenges
American poetry.

01:04:25.310 --> 01:04:28.770
It challenges American
poetry about what is poetry.

01:04:28.770 --> 01:04:33.410
Is poetry about simply, you know,
talking about flowers and plants

01:04:33.410 --> 01:04:37.970
or can poetry be about politics

01:04:37.970 --> 01:04:40.450
or about spirits and
so on and so forth?

01:04:40.450 --> 01:04:42.610
Whatever it is that is brought

01:04:42.610 --> 01:04:45.900
into that conversation I think
enriches that conversation.

01:04:45.900 --> 01:04:48.710
And I think the good
news about America is

01:04:48.710 --> 01:04:53.870
that American poetry has been
open to those conversations

01:04:53.870 --> 01:04:56.250
and we don't want those
doors to shut.

01:04:56.250 --> 01:04:59.460
And so, we want to ensure that
that conversation continues

01:04:59.460 --> 01:05:01.630
and that becomes --
that we become a place

01:05:01.630 --> 01:05:05.430
in which the world's poetry
can be articulated and spoken.

01:05:05.430 --> 01:05:08.070
Now, I might be saying that just
because I'm here in American,

01:05:08.070 --> 01:05:09.590
because probably if
I was in England,

01:05:09.590 --> 01:05:12.380
I would say the British
tradition has been very open.

01:05:12.380 --> 01:05:14.910
No. But I think it's true.

01:05:14.910 --> 01:05:16.890
I think it's uniquely
true about America.

01:05:16.890 --> 01:05:20.370
I don't think that's
an invention at all.

