01:11:51.660 --> 01:11:52.960
that [inaudible] about --

01:11:52.960 --> 01:11:54.260
&gt;&gt; Kwame Dawes: About
-- that's right.

01:11:54.260 --> 01:11:56.190
&gt;&gt; Into English.

01:11:56.190 --> 01:12:02.970
Because as a child, I think
my mother read me [inaudible]

01:12:02.970 --> 01:12:04.340
over and over again.

01:12:04.340 --> 01:12:05.640
I think [inaudible] --

01:12:05.640 --> 01:12:06.940
&gt;&gt; Kwame Dawes: Oh,
it would be fantastic.

01:12:06.940 --> 01:12:08.240
But, you know, [inaudible]
did a lot of --

01:12:08.240 --> 01:12:09.890
[inaudible] and Anita Hoe
[assumed spelling] have done a lot

01:12:09.890 --> 01:12:13.750
of translation from
[inaudible] into English.

01:12:13.750 --> 01:12:17.140
So they -- so we're looking
at some of their work.

01:12:17.140 --> 01:12:19.790
Some of [inaudible]'s poems are
translated from [inaudible].

01:12:19.790 --> 01:12:21.090
So -- and it's true.

01:12:21.090 --> 01:12:22.980
There's a long tradition
of that and in the north,

01:12:22.980 --> 01:12:26.860
there are all the proverbs,
which are --

01:12:26.860 --> 01:12:32.330
there's a fantastic process of
women taking traditional proverbs

01:12:32.330 --> 01:12:34.350
and making them feminist.

01:12:34.350 --> 01:12:36.190
This is -- these women
haven't had any encounter

01:12:36.190 --> 01:12:39.230
with Betty [inaudible]
or anybody like that.

01:12:39.230 --> 01:12:44.660
But they are actually creating this
resistance through this rewriting

01:12:44.660 --> 01:12:48.150
of proverbs that have been
historically men's problems.

01:12:48.150 --> 01:12:52.640
There's a woman called [inaudible]
who is a professor in Leguan

01:12:52.640 --> 01:12:55.130
who is doing work on that project.

01:12:55.130 --> 01:12:58.290
So -- and we see that as part
of a larger poetics agenda

01:12:58.290 --> 01:13:00.860
that we are interested in look at.

01:13:00.860 --> 01:13:05.010 position:56%
So that -- it's absolutely something
that should be done, has been done,

01:13:05.010 --> 01:13:07.470
but we would love to
publish more of that work.

01:13:07.470 --> 01:13:14.410
Yeah. We can do one more?

01:13:14.410 --> 01:13:16.820
Yes. Hello.

01:13:16.820 --> 01:13:19.910
&gt;&gt; Question about your own work.

01:13:19.910 --> 01:13:21.210
&gt;&gt; Kwame Dawes: Yes.

01:13:21.210 --> 01:13:25.080 position:56%
&gt;&gt; After growing up in the Caribbean
and Africa, living for a long time

01:13:25.080 --> 01:13:31.180
in South Carolina, which has a real
rich African-American culture --

01:13:31.180 --> 01:13:33.320
&gt;&gt; Kwame Dawes: Absolutely.

01:13:33.320 --> 01:13:35.650
&gt;&gt; Kwame Dawes: -- then,
you moved to Nebraska.

01:13:35.650 --> 01:13:45.250 position:56%
Don't want to stereotype the farm
belt, but it's a very different kind

01:13:45.250 --> 01:13:50.120
of place and I wonder how
that's influenced your work

01:13:50.120 --> 01:13:51.420
and your perspective.

01:13:51.420 --> 01:13:52.720
&gt;&gt; Kwame Dawes: It's a
very different place.

01:13:52.720 --> 01:13:54.020
Yeah. You know, here's the thing.

01:13:54.020 --> 01:13:55.320
I've moved so much.

01:13:55.320 --> 01:13:59.340 position:56%
I've moved enough, anyway, and lived
in enough places, not as many --

01:13:59.340 --> 01:14:01.310
as much as other people, I
really believe that the --

01:14:01.310 --> 01:14:05.490 position:56%
that as a poet, I have to understand
my body in any place that I live in

01:14:05.490 --> 01:14:09.330
and there are things that
my body carries with it.

01:14:09.330 --> 01:14:13.090
And it will emerge in my poetry,
but even as I live in that space,

01:14:13.090 --> 01:14:18.500
my body collects this --
the details of that space.

01:14:18.500 --> 01:14:21.460
So there is a kind of kumbaya sense

01:14:21.460 --> 01:14:23.890
of all humanity is one
and so on and so forth.

01:14:23.890 --> 01:14:28.420
But the truth is I can't
shake my own discourse

01:14:28.420 --> 01:14:30.060
and my own narrative history.

01:14:30.060 --> 01:14:34.770
So what has to happen is as much
as I might evolve or change,

01:14:34.770 --> 01:14:37.600
Nebraska is going to
have to accommodate me.

01:14:37.600 --> 01:14:39.280
Do you understand?

01:14:39.280 --> 01:14:41.990
So Nebraska changes by my presence.

01:14:41.990 --> 01:14:44.490
This is how I believe it works.

01:14:44.490 --> 01:14:46.980
This is how I believe it
worked in South Carolina.

01:14:46.980 --> 01:14:49.250
This is how I believe it
worked in New Brunswick.

01:14:49.250 --> 01:14:52.200
This is -- I believe my
body changes the space

01:14:52.200 --> 01:14:54.850
and they are going to
have to deal with it.

01:14:54.850 --> 01:14:58.800
So Nebraska cannot be
comfortably just called a farm belt

01:14:58.800 --> 01:15:02.790
because there's a guy who is
there who is writing in that space

01:15:02.790 --> 01:15:07.780
who is not deciding to run away
from the reality of being there.

01:15:07.780 --> 01:15:09.820
So I think that's how
the world's changed.

01:15:09.820 --> 01:15:17.180
I think that's how cultures begin
to evolve, not simply by them sort

01:15:17.180 --> 01:15:20.170
of creating what is rigidly there,
but when you bring something

01:15:20.170 --> 01:15:22.840
into that space, it
changes that space.

01:15:22.840 --> 01:15:26.810
That space, in changing and
accommodating becomes a new space

01:15:26.810 --> 01:15:28.200
and an interesting space.

01:15:28.200 --> 01:15:32.550
So there's a history
of Africans in Nebraska

01:15:32.550 --> 01:15:35.940
and how do we deal with that?

01:15:35.940 --> 01:15:38.690
I'll say this very short story.

01:15:38.690 --> 01:15:44.030
In South Carolina, I became
very quickly African-American,

01:15:44.030 --> 01:15:45.390
and comfortably so.

01:15:45.390 --> 01:15:49.250
And in fact, I was fast -- I
was more South Carolinian --

01:15:49.250 --> 01:15:53.490
I became South Carolinian
before I became American.

01:15:53.490 --> 01:15:56.980
I comfortably was embraced
by the black community there

01:15:56.980 --> 01:15:59.930
and I was an African-American.

01:15:59.930 --> 01:16:03.100
I get to Nebraska and I'm
suddenly, for the first time

01:16:03.100 --> 01:16:05.800
in years, Guyanean again.

01:16:05.800 --> 01:16:10.130
Why? Because Nebraska
doesn't have a narrative

01:16:10.130 --> 01:16:14.900
around African-American identity
except in an alien sort of way.

01:16:14.900 --> 01:16:19.870
And I found that fascinating,
how quickly the space decides

01:16:19.870 --> 01:16:23.900
to locate you by what it's
comfortable with and how you have

01:16:23.900 --> 01:16:29.060
to assert that solidarity and
that connection even among

01:16:29.060 --> 01:16:31.480
African-Americans in that space.

01:16:31.480 --> 01:16:34.280
And I am an annoying
person so I assert it.

01:16:34.280 --> 01:16:36.800
You know, that's my job.

01:16:36.800 --> 01:16:44.230
Right? And my poetry is the way
that I say I'm talking to you.

01:16:44.230 --> 01:16:46.910
Right? You know, Bob
Marley sings, "It's you.

01:16:46.910 --> 01:16:48.520
It's you I'm talking to.

01:16:48.520 --> 01:16:50.360
Yes, it's you.

01:16:50.360 --> 01:16:51.660
You I'm talking to.

01:16:51.660 --> 01:16:53.340 position:56%
Why do you look so sad and forsaken?

01:16:53.340 --> 01:16:57.670
When one door is closed,
many more is open."

01:16:57.670 --> 01:16:59.290
It's you I'm talking to.

01:16:59.290 --> 01:17:04.060
So if I'm in Nebraska,
people, I'm talking to you.

01:17:04.060 --> 01:17:05.580
So deal with it.

01:17:05.580 --> 01:17:09.990
&gt;&gt; Okay. One question
to close it out.

01:17:09.990 --> 01:17:13.350
You began your reading
talking about imagination

01:17:13.350 --> 01:17:15.330
and the importance of imagination.

01:17:15.330 --> 01:17:19.590 position:56%
But then, you also made reference to
an Africanness and the critical --

01:17:19.590 --> 01:17:21.360
how it's important to you.

01:17:21.360 --> 01:17:23.970
I'm interested in the
intersection of the two,

01:17:23.970 --> 01:17:28.550
if your Africanness somehow
allows imagination for you

01:17:28.550 --> 01:17:30.890
or if they're connected or if not.

01:17:30.890 --> 01:17:32.190
&gt;&gt; Kwame Dawes: Yeah.

01:17:32.190 --> 01:17:40.570
So I think my Africanness
or the complication

01:17:40.570 --> 01:17:46.080
of my Africanness has
forced me to invent

01:17:46.080 --> 01:17:51.270
through the imagination a
line of connection and a line

01:17:51.270 --> 01:17:53.330 position:56%
of identity that gives me grounding.

01:17:53.330 --> 01:17:56.220 position:56%
And invention is not that something.

01:17:56.220 --> 01:17:58.910
Invention is pulling together facts

01:17:58.910 --> 01:18:01.580
and experiences that
create a narrative.

01:18:01.580 --> 01:18:03.660
That's what I mean by invention.

01:18:03.660 --> 01:18:07.100
Right? So one of my
mottos -- and I'm --

01:18:07.100 --> 01:18:10.300
I've been waiting for
somebody to come and knock me

01:18:10.300 --> 01:18:11.910
in the head and say I made that up.

01:18:11.910 --> 01:18:16.380
But I've had this for about 30
years, that all memory is fiction.

01:18:16.380 --> 01:18:19.820
And by that, I don't mean all
memory is made up or false,

01:18:19.820 --> 01:18:22.560
but all memory is constructed.

01:18:22.560 --> 01:18:24.420
All memory is constructed.

01:18:24.420 --> 01:18:29.000
We remember what we need to
remember and we create a narrative

01:18:29.000 --> 01:18:31.880
of ourselves by constructing it.

01:18:31.880 --> 01:18:35.560
And therefore, all that
memory is invented.

01:18:35.560 --> 01:18:39.060
And so, the truth about Africa --

01:18:39.060 --> 01:18:41.040
I mean, one of the
great things about going

01:18:41.040 --> 01:18:44.710
to that museum yesterday
is just in that little hall

01:18:44.710 --> 01:18:48.320
where you're hearing these voices
moving around so on, it almost --

01:18:48.320 --> 01:18:54.110
it brought me to tears
because invention is survival.

01:18:54.110 --> 01:19:00.920
The capacity to create, to imagine
a tomorrow, this is survival.

01:19:00.920 --> 01:19:06.010
And it's been true about
African-Americans in --

01:19:06.010 --> 01:19:07.460
and it's true about people

01:19:07.460 --> 01:19:10.860
of African descent
for a very long time.

01:19:10.860 --> 01:19:13.170
Now, it may be true about
everybody else, but, boy,

01:19:13.170 --> 01:19:15.370
it's funky with African people.

01:19:15.370 --> 01:19:17.920
It really is kind of
sweet with African people.

01:19:17.920 --> 01:19:22.170
And that invention, I
take great solace in.

01:19:22.170 --> 01:19:27.980
I take great comfort in and
I take a sense that I belong.

01:19:27.980 --> 01:19:29.280
I can speak.

01:19:29.280 --> 01:19:32.310
I have a right to speak
in this space.

01:19:32.310 --> 01:19:36.920
And don't underestimate how
important that confidence

01:19:36.920 --> 01:19:39.830
to say I have a right
to speak in this space.

01:19:39.830 --> 01:19:41.360
I'll end with one little anecdote.

01:19:41.360 --> 01:19:43.330
I remember I was in
England some years ago.

01:19:43.330 --> 01:19:46.860
I was going to read at
Cambridge University.

01:19:46.860 --> 01:19:50.490
And if you have been colonized
or lived in a colonial place,

01:19:50.490 --> 01:19:53.760
you know when you say Oxford and
Cambridge, you know, it's, like,

01:19:53.760 --> 01:19:55.330
gods and people like
that live there.

01:19:55.330 --> 01:19:56.630
That's the notion.

01:19:56.630 --> 01:19:59.350
Right? And I'm going, I
don't care about that.

01:19:59.350 --> 01:20:00.650
I'm a [inaudible].

01:20:00.650 --> 01:20:01.950
I'm a [inaudible].

01:20:01.950 --> 01:20:03.250
I fight against all
that Babylon business.

01:20:03.250 --> 01:20:06.880
And I'm talking -- I had that
confidence until I got to Cambridge

01:20:06.880 --> 01:20:10.260
and I'm sailing on their
little boats and then I --

01:20:10.260 --> 01:20:14.740
that somebody says, you know,
Robert Burns stayed in that room

01:20:14.740 --> 01:20:17.060
and this one stayed
-- and I got panicky

01:20:17.060 --> 01:20:19.650
because I said what the
heck am I doing here?

01:20:19.650 --> 01:20:23.730 position:56%
This little kid, what am I doing in
the Pythagoras room, which is, like,

01:20:23.730 --> 01:20:27.460
2,000 years old, and I'm
going to read my poetry,

01:20:27.460 --> 01:20:30.860
my little dead poetry,
to these ancient places.

01:20:30.860 --> 01:20:32.160
I got freaked out.

01:20:32.160 --> 01:20:34.170
I started to panic.

01:20:34.170 --> 01:20:38.520
And then, while we are sailing
into -- bringing this boat into t--

01:20:38.520 --> 01:20:40.440
he bunting, it's so cliche.

01:20:40.440 --> 01:20:42.940
But we're coming in
and we're getting in.

01:20:42.940 --> 01:20:47.280
I hear a sound that I
go this sounds familiar.

01:20:47.280 --> 01:20:51.390
And then, I realized
it's Bob Marley's voice.

01:20:51.390 --> 01:20:56.490
There's Bob Marley music playing
and I'm on this river in Cambridge

01:20:56.490 --> 01:20:59.710
and wafting through
the air is Bob Marley.

01:20:59.710 --> 01:21:05.880
And I just thought,
well, if Bob is here

01:21:05.880 --> 01:21:09.310
and he's not giving a
damn, then I'm good.

01:21:09.310 --> 01:21:11.850
Then I'm good.

01:21:11.850 --> 01:21:16.260
And that confidence
is not a small thing.

01:21:16.260 --> 01:21:20.910
Because we have been
denied that confidence

01:21:20.910 --> 01:21:23.810
as a people again and
again and again.

01:21:23.810 --> 01:21:27.400
This work we are doing is
to bring that confidence

01:21:27.400 --> 01:21:31.400
by saying there is a history,
there is a tradition, there is --

01:21:31.400 --> 01:21:34.850
it comes from somewhere and it's
somewhere that we should embrace

01:21:34.850 --> 01:21:37.680
and be proud of because we
need to have that confidence.

01:21:37.680 --> 01:21:41.910
A lot of people take that for
granted, but it's a big deal

01:21:41.910 --> 01:21:45.590
to have the confidence to say
I'm going to write in this space

01:21:45.590 --> 01:21:48.360
and I belong in that conversation.

01:21:48.360 --> 01:21:49.660
So that's it.

